Fig 4 Types of porches and entry ways

A Roofed porch

C Vaulted entry way

See how to measure height of porches &
entry features in Figs 6-8 on pp. 11-13

B Roofed entry way
(not vaulted)

D Combination porch & vaulted entry way

visual_elements.description: Diagram A: An illustration of a 'Roofed porch' with a gabled roof, supported by four columns, and a front door. There are benches on either side of the door.

Diagram C: An illustration of a 'Vaulted entry way' for a multi-story building. It features a central arched entry with double doors, flanked by windows with shutters. The roof has dormer windows. A vertical dimension line indicates 'Height greater than 12' above grade'.

Diagram B: An illustration of a 'Roofed entry way (not vaulted)' for a single-story house. It shows a small, gabled entry porch with a single door. A vertical dimension line indicates 'Height less than 12' above grade'.

Diagram D: An illustration of a 'Combination porch & vaulted entry way'. It depicts a structure with multiple arched openings, columns, and a central vaulted entry with a door. A vertical dimension line indicates 'Height greater than 12' above grade'.

technical_specifications.parameter: Height for Combination porch & vaulted entry way (D)

structural_elements.main_heading: Fig 4 Types of porches and entry ways
sections: D Combination porch & vaulted entry way

additional_notes: The text 'Height greater than 12' above grade' appears three times, once for diagram C and once for diagram D, and once for diagram B, but for diagram B it says 'less than 12' above grade'.
A grey rectangular box in the middle of the page contains instructional text.
cross_references: Figs 6-8 on pp. 11-13 (for measuring height of porches & entry features)
